# LLM Wiki (Karpathy pattern + OKF v0.1)

## Purpose

Turn substantive work into a **durable knowledgebase** — facts, constraints, decisions, and "do not repeat" mistakes — following the [Karpathy LLM Wiki pattern](https://gist.github.com/karpathy/442a6bf555914893e9891c11519de94f) and the [Open Knowledge Format (OKF) v0.1](https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/knowledge-catalog/blob/main/okf/SPEC.md).

**Authoritative format contract:** OKF v0.1. Local summary: [`wiki/references/okf-v0.1.md`](../../wiki/references/okf-v0.1.md). Do not invent a parallel schema under `docs/`.

**Roles:** the user steers topics and sources; agents write and cross-link concept pages, keep the catalog and log current, and evolve this rule with the user. Workspace routing lives in [`AGENTS.md`](../../AGENTS.md).

## Layers

**Flow:** raw sources → curated wiki (OKF bundle) → ops contract (this rule).

| Layer | Location | Who edits |
|-------|----------|-----------|
| Raw sources (immutable) | [`wiki/raw/`](../../wiki/raw/) | User drops files; agents read only |
| OKF bundle (concepts + indexes + log) | [`wiki/`](../../wiki/) | Agents create/update pages, cross-links, index, log |
| Ops contract | This file | Human + agent co-evolve |

The `wiki/` directory **is** the OKF knowledge bundle (`okf_version: "0.1"` in root `index.md`).

## OKF conformance (MUST)

A change is conformant only if:

1. Every **non-reserved** `.md` file under `wiki/` has parseable YAML frontmatter with a non-empty `type`.
2. Reserved filenames `index.md` and `log.md` follow OKF §6 / §7 (see below).
3. Do **not** use `index.md` or `log.md` as concept documents.

Reserved: `index.md`, `log.md`. All other `.md` files are concepts.

### Concept frontmatter

```yaml
---
type: <Type name>                  # REQUIRED (only required field)
title: <Optional display name>
description: <Optional one-line summary>
resource: <Optional canonical URI>
tags: [<tag>, <tag>, …]
timestamp: <ISO 8601 datetime>
# … additional producer-defined keys allowed
---
```

- Prefer recommended fields (`title`, `description`, `tags`, `timestamp`; `resource` when describing a tangible asset).
- `type` values are open (e.g. `Workspace`, `Entity`, `Topic`, `Reference`, `KnownIssue`) — not centrally registered.

### Index files (§6)

- No frontmatter except the **bundle-root** `index.md`, which MAY declare `okf_version: "0.1"`.
- Body: one or more `#` sections with bullet entries: `* [Title](path) - short description`.
- Entries SHOULD reuse the linked concept's `description`. Subdirectories MAY be linked with a trailing `/`.

### Log files (§7)

Newest first. Date headings MUST be `YYYY-MM-DD`. Entries are prose; a leading bold verb is conventional:

```markdown
# Directory Update Log

## 2026-07-10
* **Update**: Short description with optional [links](/path/to/concept.md).
* **Creation**: …
```

### Cross-links (§5)

Prefer **bundle-absolute** links (`/workspace/overview.md`) for in-bundle targets. Relative links are allowed. Broken links are not malformed.

### Citations (§8)

When claims come from external material, list them under `# Citations` at the bottom of the concept.

## Operations

- **Ingest** — Read sources or conversation; write/update concept pages; refresh affected `index.md` files; append `log.md`.
- **Query** — Read `wiki/index.md` first, then drill into linked pages; file durable answers back into the wiki.
- **Lint** — On request, when the wiki is large, or when the user invokes **`@wiki-lint`** — follow [**Lint**](#lint) below.

## When to update (no reminder needed)

Do **not** wait for "put this in the wiki." After **substantive** work, if any of this became true, integrate it before stopping:

- A non-obvious fact, constraint, or command that will matter in a **later** session.
- A mistake, false assumption, or fix worth **not repeating**.
- A stable decision or rationale not captured in an ADR, plan, or existing wiki page.
- A good synthesis, comparison, or answer the user might ask again — **file it**.

Skip trivia, secrets, one-off typos, or anything already the single source of truth in `docs/specs/` (link instead).

## What to touch each time

1. **Create or edit** the relevant concept page(s) under `wiki/` (OKF frontmatter + body).
2. Update [`wiki/index.md`](../../wiki/index.md) and the subdirectory `index.md` for any new/changed page.
3. Append to [`wiki/log.md`](../../wiki/log.md) under today's `## YYYY-MM-DD` heading (create the heading if needed; keep newest dates first).
4. Prefer bundle-absolute links for in-wiki targets.

## Query habit

When the user asks something that may already be compiled, **read `wiki/index.md` first**, then open linked pages. Prefer citing/updating the wiki over rediscovering from scratch.

## Lint

**Purpose:** review `wiki/` for OKF consistency and navigability.

Run when the user invokes **`@wiki-lint`**, when pages grow stale, or when the wiki exceeds ~50 pages.

**Scope:** all markdown under `wiki/` except `wiki/raw/` (immutable).

**Checks:**
1. **OKF conformance** — every concept has frontmatter + non-empty `type`; `index.md` / `log.md` match §6 / §7; root `index.md` declares `okf_version`.
2. **Staleness** — pages whose `timestamp` predates newer contradicting pages.
3. **Orphans** — concept pages with no inbound links from an `index.md` or another concept.
4. **Coverage gaps** — concepts mentioned across pages but lacking their own page.
5. **Broken links** — note missing targets (tolerated by OKF; still worth fixing when known).
6. **Duplicate detection** — near-identical titles or concept IDs.

**Actions:** list concrete edits (path + intent). Apply safe markdown-only fixes (cross-links, index rows, log append). Leave structural changes as recommendations. Log the pass to `wiki/log.md`.
